  "text": "GCC implements stack clash protection primarily through a generic mechanism in gcc/explow.cc that is used across multiple target architectures including x86_64. The implementation architecture follows this call chain:\n\n1. **Entry Point (gcc/common.opt, gcc/params.opt)**: The -fstack-clash-protection flag is defined at gcc/common.opt:3054-3057 as an optimization flag. Two related parameters control the behavior: stack-clash-protection-guard-size (gcc/params.opt:1108-1110) and stack-clash-protection-probe-interval (gcc/params.opt:1112-1114), both representing powers of 2 for guard and probe distances.\n\n2. **Compilation and Validation (gcc/toplev.cc)**: At lines 1650-1656, the compiler validates that stack clash protection is not used on targets where the stack grows upward (which would make the protection ineffective). The -fstack-clash-protection flag is rejected for such targets.\n\n3. **Target Hook Interface (gcc/target.def, gcc/targhooks.*)**: The mechanism provides a target hook TARGET_STACK_CLASH_PROTECTION_ALLOCA_PROBE_RANGE (gcc/target.def:6534-6545) allowing architectures to define ABI-specific probe ranges. The default implementation in gcc/targhooks.cc:2744+ (default_stack_clash_protection_alloca_probe_range) returns 0, allowing generic behavior. Function prototypes are declared in gcc/targhooks.h:305.\n\n4. **Generic Implementation (gcc/explow.cc, gcc/explow.h)**: The core stack clash protection logic resides in gcc/explow.cc:\n\n   a. **allocate_dynamic_stack_space (gcc/explow.cc:1443+)**: High-level function that allocates dynamic stack space. When flag_stack_clash_protection is set, it calls anti_adjust_stack_and_probe_stack_clash instead of the standard anti_adjust_stack_and_probe (lines 1645-1646).\n\n   b. **anti_adjust_stack_and_probe_stack_clash (gcc/explow.cc:2072-2142)**: Implements the stack clash protection mechanism for dynamic allocations. This function:\n      - Ensures the size is in Pmode (line 2075-2076)\n      - Calls compute_stack_clash_protection_loop_data to calculate probe parameters (line 2082-2083)\n      - Retrieves target-specific probe range via targetm.stack_clash_protection_alloca_probe_range() (line 2086)\n      - For small allocations (≤4*probe_interval), emits inline probes (line 2098-2108)\n      - For larger allocations, emits a probing loop using emit_stack_clash_protection_probe_loop_start/end\n\n   c. **compute_stack_clash_protection_loop_data (gcc/explow.cc:1955-2004)**: Calculates loop parameters:\n      - Extracts probe_interval from param_stack_clash_protection_probe_interval (line 1961-1962)\n      - Rounds the allocation size down to probe_interval boundary (line 1963-1964)\n      - Computes the final stack pointer value (last_addr) (line 1969-1972)\n      - Calculates residual bytes not covered by the loop (line 1976)\n\n   d. **emit_stack_clash_protection_probe_loop_start (gcc/explow.cc:2014+)**: Emits RTL instructions for loop initialization, including loop label and initial comparison.\n\n   e. **emit_stack_clash_protection_probe_loop_end (gcc/explow.cc:2036+)**: Emits RTL instructions for the loop body and termination logic.\n\n5. **x86_64 Integration (gcc/config/i386/i386.cc)**: While the generic mechanism in gcc/explow.cc handles most of the work, gcc/config/i386/i386.cc provides x86-specific prologue/epilogue generation and frame management. The x86 backend leverages the generic stack clash protection functions defined in gcc/explow.cc.\n\n6. **Function Declarations (gcc/explow.h:70-87)**: All stack clash protection functions are declared as:\n   - anti_adjust_stack_and_probe_stack_clash(rtx) (line 78)\n   - compute_stack_clash_protection_loop_data(...) (lines 82-83)\n   - emit_stack_clash_protection_probe_loop_start(...) (lines 84-85)\n   - emit_stack_clash_protection_probe_loop_end(...) (lines 86-87)\n\n7. **Testing (gcc/testsuite/gcc.target/i386/)**: Comprehensive test coverage is provided:\n   - Primary test: gcc/testsuite/gcc.target/i386/stack-clash-protection.c (basic compilation test)\n   - Stack check tests: stack-check-11.c through stack-check-19.c (various frame and optimization scenarios)\n   - Issue regression tests: pr84128.c, pr83994.c, pr84064.c (specific bug fixes)\n   - Test framework: gcc/testsuite/lib/target-supports.exp:13634 defines check_effective_target_supports_stack_clash_protection\n\n**Key Design Features**:\n- The implementation is **generic and reusable** across architectures (x86_64, ARM64, PowerPC, RISC-V, LoongArch, S390 all use it)\n- **Parameterizable guard and probe sizes** controlled via compiler parameters\n- **Intelligent loop generation** that unrolls small allocations inline and uses loops for larger allocations\n- **Target-specific customization** through hook mechanism allowing architectures to define ABI-specific behavior\n- **Mutual exclusivity** with -fstack-check mode enforced at compilation time\n\n**Protection Mechanism**:\nStack clash attacks exploit gaps between stack probes by allocating memory in chunks smaller than the probing interval, allowing an attacker to jump over the guard page. This implementation prevents this by:\n1. Probing at regular intervals (typically 4KB on x86)\n2. Never skipping probes even for small allocations\n3. Using mandatory probes for all dynamic allocations when -fstack-clash-protection is enabled\n4. Respecting the OS guard page size (typically 4KB on Linux)"
